<TITLE> UK goods trade deficit narrows in Aug </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Oct 9 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Britain's goods trade deficit with the rest of the world narrowed as expected in August as the value of exports rose to its highest in a year, official statistics showed on Tuesday. The Office for National Statistics said that Britain's goods trade gap shrank to 6.853 billion pounds, in line with forecasts. The goods trade gap with non-EU countries narrowed to 3.902 billion pounds, also broadly in line with expectations. A breakdown of the figures showed the value of exports rose to 18.975 billion pounds -- its highest since August 2006 and suggesting that strong global growth has outweighed the impact of the strong pound. The oil deficit increased to 506 million pounds, its highest in a year, as annual maintenance work depressed production volumes, while sales to the domestic market were high. Import prices excluding oil and erratics rose by 0.2 percent in August, after falling in the previous two months. However, on a 3-month/3-month basis, prices fell by 0.4 percent, the biggest decline since April 2004. The ONS said that fall was driven by a decline in the price of gas and electricity as well as precious stones and silv
